documents.content: Japan raises some of the most respectful kids on earth but not through strict rules. The secret is a may, a parenting strategy that builds such deep emotional security that children obey out of connection, not fear. Closeness comes before discipline in Japan. Japanese parents avoid power struggles altogether. They repeat expectations calmly without changing the boundary. Kids feel proud of doing real tasks. They see themselves as helpers not burdens. Confident kids fight less, cooperate more and respect boundaries naturally.
documents.originalNote: Japan raises some of the most respectful kids on earth but not through strict rules. The secret is a may, a parenting strategy that builds such deep emotional security that children obey out of connection, not fear. Here is how this creates kids who listen the first time. A may creates a bond that makes obedience natural. It means letting a child depend on you fully in the early years. A secure child does not fight for attention. They already feel seen and kids who feel seen listen more willingly. Japanese obedience starts with emotional safety, not discipline. Before asking children to listen, the parents build an uncheekable bond. Kids who feel deeply secure do not fight for attention. They already have it and children who feel safe listen faster. Closeness comes before discipline in Japan. Mother's stiff physically near their toddlers throughout the day. The response quickly to needs the nurture connection through touch, tone and attention. When trust is strong, cooperation becomes a firtless. Japanese parents teach through modeling, not lectures. Children watch before they act. If a parent wants the room clean, they calmly tidy first. Kids imitate what they see. Behavior comes, becomes something absorbed, not forced. Imitation is the strongest form of learning. Children absorb tone, rhythm, and behavior like sponges. No lecture needed. Children mirror the emotional climate they grow up in. The power of V makes listening natural. Japanese parents rarely say do this because I said so. They say let's think about everyone. This teaches empathy early. Empathy makes kids more cooperative and aware. Kids behave respectfully when they understand impact. A loud child in a restaurant here lets use quite voices so others can enjoy their meal. They learn their actions affect people around them. Respect is taught through awareness not fear. Natural consequences replace punishment. If a child refuses a jacket, they feel the cold. If they break a toy, the toy is gone. Parents take calm and supportive. Reality becomes the teacher, not anger. This creates kids who make better choices, even when no one is watching. They learn, cause and effect directly. They do not obey out of fear, they obey because it makes sense. Japanese children are trusted with real responsibilities early. Three-year child help set tables, six-year-olds, serve classmates, lunch, old students clean their own rooms, responsibility becomes identity not punishment. Contribution builds confidence faster than praise. Kids feel proud of doing real tasks. They see themselves as helpers not burdens. This deepens a self-worth. Confident kids fight less, cooperate more and respect boundaries naturally. Japanese parents avoid power struggles altogether. They use gentle persistence, they repeat expectations calmly without changing the boundary. The tone stays soft, the limit stays firm. Kids learn that listening is expected, not negotiated. Emotional regulation is taught through calm presence. When a child mades down, parents become the anchor. They take loads, speak softly and wait for the storm to pass. Children learn that big feelings are safe over time. They mirror the calm they see.

Build a web-based application that allows users to capture, organize, and refine business requirements efficiently, with AI-assisted refinement for clarity and completeness.

Product Owner

Business Analysts

Development Team

QA Team

End Users / Clients

Target Users

Business analysts

Product managers

Startup founders

IT teams gathering project requirements

Rich text input for writing requirements

AI-powered refinement and restructuring of notes

Voice input support for quick requirement capture

Save, edit, and manage multiple requirement notes

Export refined requirements (PDF / DOC / text)

Clean, distraction-free UI for focused writing

Non-Functional Requirements

Fast response time for AI refinement

Secure handling of user data

Responsive design for desktop and tablet

Scalable architecture for future enhancements

Constraints

Fixed initial release timeline

Limited budget for Phase 1

AI usage limits based on plan

A polished, well-structured requirements document that can be directly shared with developers or clients, reducing back-and-forth clarification and saving time.

ITSM      Agent   Guide 2025  Office Address:   Suratwala Mark Plazzo, Hinjawadi, Pune, Maharashtra 411057  Support Call:   8956268998   Mail :   support@cybaemtech.com
## Agent      Complete Guide (Dashboard      Settings)  This document covers the full Agent experience: what you see in the UI, how to use each  section step - by - step, and tips for common workflows. It maps directly to the components  and pages in the codebase (see references at the end).  Audience: Agents and Admins (role - specific notes included where admin - only functionality  exists).  Contents  -   Dashboard (home / admin/dashboard)  -   Tickets (list, filters, search, ticket detail, edit)  -   Create Ticket (full form, dialogs, attachments)  -   Knowledge Base & Documentation  -   Bug Reports / All Tickets (admin)  -   Settings (Profile, Security, Notifications, Appearance, Domains, Data)  -   Admin panels: Users, Categories, Reports  -   QA checklist, Troubleshooting, Acceptance criteria  1)   Dashboard  What you see  -   Top stats cards: Open, In Progress, Avg. Response Time, SLA metrics.  -   Recent Tickets table: quick link to ticket detail.  -   Popular FAQs, charts (weekly ticket volume, category distribution), quick access  cards(Users, Categories, Reports).  Agent steps & actions  -   Review Open and In - Progress counts to prioritize work.  -   Click a ticket in Recent Tickets to open the Ticket Detail page.  -   Use Quick Access to navigate to Users, Categories, or Reports for admin tasks.
Tips  -   Use the SLA Compliance card to detect potential escalations.  -   Charts show trends      use them when reporting weekly performance.  2)   Tickets list  Visible sections  -   Search bar: free - text search across title, description, and ticket ID.  -   Filters: Status, Priority, Category.  -   Tickets table: ID, Title, Status, Priority, Created, Actions (View, Comments).  -   New Ticket button      navigates to create page.  Agent steps & actions  -   Filter by status/priority to find urgent items.  -   Use the search box for quick ID lookup      format TKT - #### or partial text.  -   Open ticket for details, or use action buttons for quick view/comment.  Edge cases  -   If filters return no results, clear filters and check the global All Tickets page (admins  cansee everything).  3)   Ticket Detail  What you see  -   Header: Ticket ID, title, created date, created by, status badge, priority badge.  -   Main column: description, attachments, comments thread, add comment form.  -   Side column: Status panel (editable for agents/admins), Assigned To (admin  assigndropdown + 'Assign to me' button), Priority selector, Details panel (company,  location, category, last updated), Related articles.  Agent steps & actions
-   Change status: use the Status dropdown (Open, In Progress, Closed).  -   Assign to agent: admin dropdown or use the 'Assign to me' button (agents canquick -  assign themselves). Assignment verifies server - side and will notify if assignment status  couldn't be verified.  -   Add comment: use the comment box. Agents/admins may toggle "Internal note" to  keepcontent private from the requester.  -   Update priority via the Priority selector.  -   Download or view attachments via Download button in the attachment panel.  Common flows  -   Reassigning: choose a different agent, or unassign (admin only).  -   Add internal note: toggle internal flag      internal notes are not visible to end users.  4)   Create Ticket      combined, detailed agent guidance  This section consolidates the ticket - creation details and maps each UI field/dialog to agent  actions and validations. Use this as the canonical reference when creating tickets on  behalf of users.  Overview      intent and high - level flow  -   Purpose: create a support ticket that is routed, assigned (optional), and tracked.  -   Role: Agents and Admins can create tickets for other users; regular Users create  ticketsfor themselves (covered in the user guide).  Field - by - field (what you see and concrete actions)  -   Ticket Title  -   What: single - line summary.  -   Visibility: shown to all roles.  -   Validation: required; 5  100 characters enforced by client - side zod schema.  -   Agent action: write a concise, action - oriented title (e.g., "VPN intermittent for  Financeteam").
-   Description  -   What: multi - line details area.  -   Visibility: all roles; internal notes are handled on the ticket detail page.  -   Agent action: include steps to reproduce, screenshots references, timestamps, and  anyprevious troubleshooting.  -   Category and Subcategory  -   What: dropdowns populated by server categories; agents can  addcategories/subcategories inline.  -   Visibility: all roles (agents/admins typically have more category options).  -   Agent action: choose the most specific category first; if missing, use      Add New  Category / Add New Subcategory buttons in the dropdown to create entries (these call  POST /api/categories and update UI immediately).  -   Contact Information (Agents/Admins only)  -   What: select an existing user (contact) or create one via "Add New User" dialog.  -   Behavior: selecting a contact auto - fills contactEmail, contactName,  contactPhone,contactDepartment, companyName, and location.  -   Agent action: always prefer selecting the existing user record; if the requester  doesn'texist, use Add New User (creates user via POST /api/users and attaches created  user's id to the ticket).  -   Assigned To / Quick Assign  -   What: Admins can choose any agent from dropdown; agents have an "Assign to  me"quick toggle.  -   Behavior: After ticket creation, client code verifies assignment via GET /api/tickets/:id  andretries PUT /api/tickets/:id to set assignedToId if needed (up to 3 retries). If  verification fails, the UI displays a toast and the ticket is still created.  -   Agent action: use quick - assign to take ownership; Admins should explicitly assign to  theappropriate team member.  -   Priority  -   What: low/medium/high.  -   Visibility: visible to agents/admins and, in some setups, to users (users can suggest  butagents override final priority).
-   Agent action: set priority according to SLA and impact.  -   Support Type  -   What: remote, telephonic, onsite_visit, other.  -   Agent action: pick the mode of support expected.  -   Company Name & Location  -   What: auto - filled when contact is selected; editable fields.  -   Agent action: confirm these are accurate especially when opening tickets for  externalcontacts.  -   Attachments  -   What: drag - and - drop/file selector accepting PNG/JPG/PDF/DOC/DOCX; client  limitshown is 10MB.  -   Agent action: attach logs/screenshots; if upload fails, compress or provide alternateshare  link.  -   Due Date (optional)  -   What: optional ISO date string field that gets converted to toISOString on submit.  -   Agent action: set when an SLA or explicit due date is known.  Dialogs and inline actions  -   Add New Category / Subcategory: opens a Dialog, sends POST /api/categories  withparentId null or category id, updates local categories and refetches the categories  query.  -   Add New User: opens a Dialog, sends POST /api/users with role "user"  andautogenerated password; on success auto - selects created user as contact.  -   Add New Agent: similar to Add New User but role "agent"; on success can auto - selectthe  agent as assignedTo.  Validation, errors and server interactions  -   Client validation: enforced by zod schema (title length, category required, email formatfor  contactEmail).
-   Server errors: displayed via toast. For validation errors, the client shows a  friendlymessage. For 5xx/database errors, the message suggests retry and contacting  support.  -   Assignment verification: client performs checks and will show a warning toast if it  cannotverify the assignment.  Step - by - step agent example (create for another user)  1.   Header: Tickets      Create New Support Ticket.  2.   Title: Enter "Unable to access payroll server" (ensure5+  chars).  3.   Category: select "Network & Connectivity"      Subcategory "Server access".  4.   Contact Info: choose the user's account (search  byemail). Confirm auto - filled company and location.  5.   Priority: set to High.  6.   Assigned To: choose the specialist agent or click "Assign to me".  7.   Support Type: select Remote.  8.   Attach a screenshot and any server logs (confirm  eachfile is < 10MB).  9.   Click Create Ticket.  10.   Confirm toast success and navigate to Ticket Detail for follow - up. If  assignmentverification fails, reassign manually from Ticket Detail.  Acceptance criteria for agent - created tickets  -   Ticket created with a unique ID and appears in ticket lists.  -   If assigned, verify assignedToId matches the selected agent (or UI warns if  verificationfailed).  -   Requester receives notification if notifications are enabled.
5)   Knowledge Base & Documentation  Usage  -   Search or browse FAQs and documentation to find troubleshooting steps.  -   Related articles are surfaced on ticket detail pages based on category/subcategory.  Agent steps  -   Use KB links when responding to users to reduce time - to - resolution.  -   If article missing, create or request new KB content and link it from the ticket detail  orinternal notes.  6)   Bug Reports  Usage  -   Submit bug reports separate from customer tickets (usually for product issues).  Agent steps  -   Triage bug reports, add labels, assign to engineering, and link relevant tickets or PRs.  7)   Settings      agent/admin sections  Tabs and fields  -   Profile: name, email, company, department, designation, contact number.  -   Security: change password, enable 2FA (placeholder), login notifications.  -   Notifications: toggles for email/push, ticket updates, assignment notifications,  weeklyreports, maintenance alerts.  -   Appearance: theme, language, timezone, date/time format.  -   Domains (admin/agent only): add/edit/disable allowed domains for registration (fullCRUD  with confirmation for deletes).  -   Data: export (download JSON), import, Danger Zone (delete account).
Admin - specific actions  -   Domain management: add allowed domains to gate registrations.  -   Export data for a user, manage imports, delete accounts via the Data tab (danger  zonewarnings present).  8)   Admin panels  -   Users  -   Create/update users, change roles (user/agent/admin), disable or delete accounts.  -   Categories  -   Manage categories/subcategories; used by routing and KB suggestion logic.  -   Reports  -   View historical metrics, SLA compliance, performance charts.  9)   Checklist (happy path + agent - specific tests)  -   Create ticket as Agent for an existing user: ticket is created, assigned (if  chosen),appears in ticket list, notifications sent.  -   Create ticket as Agent for a new user: Add New User flow creates account and ticketsare  attached to that user.  -   Assign ticket to agent and verify assignment persists (assignment verification logic  retriesup to 3 times).  -   Add attachment > 10MB: upload is rejected with error message.  -   Add internal note: visible to agents/admins but not end users.  -   Edit profile in Settings: changes persist and visible on next fetch.

How to use  -   Click a ticket to open details (ticket ID, description, status, agent assignment,  comments).  -   Use "Create Ticket" to start a new support request.  2)   My Tickets  Visible sections  -   Search box for ticket ID or keyword.  -   Filters for status, priority, and category.  -   Tickets table with actions to view or comment.  User steps  -   Search with the ticket ID in format TKT - #### to find a specific ticket.  -   Apply filters to narrow results, then click a row to open the Ticket Detail.
3)   C r e a t e   T i c k e t   -   c o mbined, detailed user guidance  This section includes the exact fields you will see when creating a ticket and step - by - step  instructions tailored for end users.  Visible fields & what they mean  -   Ticket Title  -   Short summary of the problem.  -   Required. Validation: 5  100 characters.  -   Description  -   Provide steps to reproduce, error messages, and what you expect to happen.  -   The more details, the faster agents can diagnose the issue.  -   Category / Subcategory  -   Helps route your ticket to the correct team. Attachments: add a screenshot of the error (if available).  9.   Click Submit / Create Ticket.  10.   Observe confirmation and copy the Ticket ID for reference.
